content.description: An overhung problem a few feet left of Slack (V2). Sit under the overhang on a good foot rail just above ground level. Undercling the lip above your head and work your way up the roof to a good sloper before traversing and topping out to the left.
content.location: On the largest boulder formation at the overlook, 5-10 feet left of Slack (V2).

content.description: This problem climbs a thin finger crack up the slab to an easy top out.
content.protection: One pad (two for some adjacent problems would be nice)
content.location: From the "Ceder Boulders" Walk downhill through the woods to where things open up a bit. Walk down to until you find the two largest boulder formations with a very short gully between them. Turn left at the bottom of this gully, following the boulder on your left side for 30 feet or so. The crack is at the end of this formation on a ~12 foot tall slab facing the river. There are 10 or so excellent climbs all along this short cliff face (both sides of the gully). Try the slab problem to the right of the crack (crack is off!)

content.description: A fun slab problem just to the right of Slack (V2). Climb so that the crack is just within reach of your left hand, but don't use it.
content.location: An arms length to the right of Slack.

content.description: Begin on two sloping sidepulls and work feet through thin holds to a thoughtful yet mild topout.

Start low on the far left side of the West Virginia block. heel hook and slap your way up and right along the slopers, a crimp or two and finally a jug. Find a way to heave yourself over the top from the jug. The adjacent boulder to the right is off. The awkward top out is made easier by a hidden hold about two feet over the lip.
content.location: Downhill from cedar boulders. Check the photos and the map.
